What is Logistic Regression?
Despite the name, it is used for classification (not regression). It predicts the probability of a binary outcome (0
or 1) using the sigmoid function
xxx

What is a confusion matrix? A: A table comparing actual vs predicted labels. It has 4 values: TP, TN, FP,
FN. It helps evaluate classifier performance.
Q: What is TP, TN, FP, FN? A: TP = Model said Yes, was Yes. TN = Model said No, was No. FP = Model
said Yes, was No (Type I Error). FN = Model said No, was Yes (Type II
Error).
Q: Difference between
Precision and Recall?
A: Precision = TP/(TP+FP) — of all predicted positives, how many are
correct. Recall = TP/(TP+FN) — of all actual positives, how many did we
find.
Q: When to use F1 vs F2 score? A: F1 when Precision and Recall are equally important. F2 when Recall is
twice as important (e.g., medical diagnosis where missing a disease is worse
than false alarm).
Q: What is an outlier? How do
you detect it?
A: Data point far from others. Detect using IQR: anything below Q1-1.5*IQR
or above Q3+1.5*IQR. Also by Z-score (|z|>3) or visually via box plot.
Q: Difference between Linear
and Logistic Regression?
A: Linear Regression predicts continuous values (house price). Logistic
Regression predicts binary/categorical outcomes (spam or not) using
sigmoid function.
Q: What is the 'naive'
assumption in Naïve Bayes?
A: All features are conditionally independent given the class. In reality
features may be correlated, but the algorithm works well despite this
assumption.
Q: What is K-Means? How to
choose K?
A: Unsupervised clustering algorithm. K = number of clusters. Choose K
using Elbow Plot — pick K where inertia curve bends.
Q: What is TF-IDF? A: Term Frequency-Inverse Document Frequency. TF = how often word
appears in doc. IDF = log(total docs / docs containing word). Words common
in all docs get low weight.
Q: Difference between
stemming and lemmatization?
A: Stemming crudely chops word endings (running→run). Lemmatization
uses dictionary to get base form (better→good). Lemmatization is more
accurate.
Q: What is AUC-ROC? A: ROC curve plots TPR vs FPR. AUC is the area — 1.0 = perfect, 0.5 =
random. Used to compare models regardless of threshold.
Q: What is data normalization?
Types?
A: Scaling features to a common range. Min-Max: scales to [0,1]. Standard
(Z-score): mean=0, std=1. Done to prevent features with large values
dominating the model.
Q: What is the Data Analytics
Lifecycle?
A: Phase 1: Discovery → Phase 2: Data Preparation → Phase 3: Model
Planning → Phase 4: Model Building → Phase 5: Communication → Phase
6: Operationalize
